This seems to be setting the exam to closed any time the exam is shown, which doesn't seem quite right.

The issue is arising because the `UserExamResource` has cached the previous call to its endpoint, so is not being updated when we navigate back to the exam list page.

I would suggest clearing this cache, once the exam has been submitted by the student. So, perhaps here, in the `closeExam` action: https://github.com/learningequality/kolibri/blob/develop/kolibri/plugins/learn/assets/src/state/actions/main.js#L673
Could be:
```
  return ExamLogResource.getModel(examLog.id)
    .save(examLog)
    .catch(error => {
      handleApiError(store, error);
    });
  return ExamLogResource.getModel(examLog.id)
    .save(examLog)
    .then(UserExamResource.clearCache)
    .catch(error => {
      handleApiError(store, error);
    });
```

This would clear the cache, once the examLog has properly saved, and before the redirect happens.

These aren't new, I've observed the same issue with Juju controllers running 2.0.2 and 2.2.3.

The schema is wrong. In particular, this bit of the Resource definition states that there's a field named CharmResource, defined by #/definitions/CharmResource:

```
"Resource": {
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "CharmResource": {
      "$ref": "#/definitions/CharmResource"
    },
    ...
  }
  ...
}
```

where #/definitions/CharmResource defines the `name` and `origin` fields:

```
"CharmResource": {
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    ...
    "name": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "origin": {
      "type": "string" 
    },
    ...
  },
  ...
},
```

However, here's the actual data I get in the response:

```
"resources": [
  {
    "username": "test/0",
    "type": "file",
    "pending-id": "",
    "name": "test-new",
    "fingerprint": "XwyivFD/IYBYXbtVo2VwSITDq8/yv+tncsHIPTnEY46+DjYpyL2JOupZXFTjSkz7",
    "revision": 3,
    "size": 10,
    "id": "test/test-new",
    "timestamp": "2017-09-27T15:07:53.923Z",
    "path": "test",
    "origin": "store",
    "application": "test"
  }
]
```

So Resource does not have a field named CharmResource. Rather, Resource _includes the fields from the CharmResource definition_. But that's not what the schema says.

After reading the [JSON Schema doc page that discusses $ref](https://spacetelescope.github.io/understanding-json-schema/structuring.html), it looks to me like the Resource definition should be using `allOf` to extend from CharmResource properly.

@johnsca Seems like I should open a bug against juju/schemagen, yeah?

